# Phase 2.1 — STATE-AUTHORITATIVE VEHICLE SYNC. Multi-week R&D.
#
# This is the BIG ONE. It flips the trust model from "driver simulates, broadcasts"
# (owner-auth, what FiveM/RAGE/altV-v1 do) to "server simulates, broadcasts state"
# (state-auth, what CS:GO/Valorant/Apex do for player movement).
#
# Why it matters:
#   - End to vehicle rubber-banding on bad-network drivers (server simulates evenly)
#   - Cheaters can't speedhack/teleport their cars — server validates physics
#   - Anti-cheat foundation: replays, hit-reg, all become consistent
#
# Why it's hard:
#   - Need to extract RAGE physics constants from GTA V (legal: read at runtime
#     via citizen-mod-loader, not redistribute)
#   - Server tick must run physics for every "authoritative" vehicle (~30 simul.)
#   - Client must trust server state more than its local prediction (snap on
#     mismatch beyond input-prediction tolerance)
#
# === High-level architecture ===
#
#   ┌────────────┐   inputs (steer, throttle, brake, ts)   ┌────────────┐
#   │   Driver   │  ──────────────────────────────────────► │   Server   │
#   │   client   │                                          │            │
#   │            │                                          │ run RAGE   │
#   │ predicts   │                                          │ physics    │
#   │ locally    │  ◄───────────────────────────────────── │ for car    │
#   │ for resp.  │   state @ ts (pos, rot, vel, ang_vel)   │ at tick    │
#   │            │                                          │            │
#   └────────────┘                                          │ broadcast  │
#                                                           │ state to   │
#   ┌────────────┐                                          │ all viewers│
#   │  Viewer    │  ◄────────────────────────────────────── │            │
#   │  client    │                state                     └────────────┘
#   └────────────┘
#
# Driver client still predicts locally (no input lag), but the server's state is
# canonical. Driver client reconciles smoothly to server (uses our Phase 1.3).
#
# === New files ===
#
#   code/components/citizen-server-impl/include/state/StateAuthority.h
#   code/components/citizen-server-impl/src/state/StateAuthority.cpp
#   code/components/citizen-server-impl/src/state/VehiclePhysics.cpp
#   code/components/gta-streaming-five/src/AuthoritativeVehicleClient.cpp
#
# === Schema additions ===
#
# Client → Server (every input frame, ~60 Hz):
#   struct VehicleInput {
#       uint64 vehicleId;
#       uint32 frameTs;             // client frame timestamp
#       int16  steerAngle_q8_7;
#       uint8  throttle, brake, handbrake, gearShift;  // q8.0
#       uint8  buttonFlags;         // horn, lights, etc
#   }                                                  // 16 bytes/frame
#
# Server → Client (response, also 60 Hz):
#   struct AuthoritativeState {
#       uint64 vehicleId;
#       uint32 ackInputTs;          // confirms which input we processed
#       Vec3   pos;
#       Quat   rot;
#       Vec3   vel, angVel;
#       uint16 health;
#       uint8  bodyDeformation[8];  // crumple zones
#   }                                                  // 64 bytes/frame
#
# === Physics tick (server-side) ===
#
# void ProcessVehicleAuthority() {
#     for (auto& [vehId, authState] : vehicleAuthority) {
#         VehicleInput latestInput = inputBuffer[vehId].getLatest();
#         RagePhysicsTick(authState, latestInput, kPhysicsDt);
#         BroadcastState(vehId, authState, latestInput.frameTs);
#     }
# }
#
# RagePhysicsTick uses constants extracted from GTA V handling.meta (mass,
# inertia, suspension, traction). These are read at startup via the existing
# CFX streaming loader.
#
# === Reconciliation ===
#
# Driver client compares its prediction at frameTs to server's state at the same
# frameTs. If divergence > 0.5 m, soft-reconcile (Phase 1.3 covers this).
# Other viewers just lerp to server state.
#
# === Convars ===
#
#   sv_authoritative_vehicles      true|false   default FALSE during beta
#   sv_authoritative_only_subscribed bool       only sim cars with drivers (saves CPU)
#   sv_auth_inputBufferFrames      4..16        client→server input buffer
#
# === Backout path ===
#
# Set sv_authoritative_vehicles false → reverts to stock OneSync owner-auth.
# No client changes needed (clients always send inputs; server just ignores them
# in owner-auth mode and trusts client snapshots).
#
# === Risk register ===
#
# 1. CPU explosion on busy server: 30 cars × 60 Hz physics = ~1.5 cores
#    busy. Mitigation: sv_authoritative_only_subscribed (skip empty cars).
# 2. Input latency feels heavier for driver if their RTT > 80 ms. Mitigation:
#    client-side prediction keeps responsiveness, server is just validation.
# 3. Determinism: same input must produce same output across server restarts.
#    Risk if we use GTA V's nondeterministic physics. Mitigation: deterministic
#    integrator using extracted handling constants.
#
# Estimated effort: 6-8 weeks of focused work + 2 weeks soak testing.
